<subsection xml:id="subsection-line-segment-congruence">
    <title>Line Segment Congruence</title>
<definition xml:id="definition-congruence">
    <statement>
        <p>
            Two geometric figures that have the same shape and size are said to be <term>congruent</term>.
        </p>
    </statement> 
</definition>

<p>Two line segments are <term>congruent segments</term> if they have the same measure or length.
</p>

<p>We denote that line segments <m>\overline{AB}</m> and <m>\overline{CD}</m> are congruent by writing <m>\overline{AB} \cong \overline{CD}</m>.
    This implies that the lengths of the segments are equal, i.e., <m>AB = CD</m>.
</p>
<p>Note well the following distinction: Two line segments can be <em>congruent</em>. Two lengths can be <em>equal</em>.
</p>
